<CaseStudy
  title="DMDS–Albumin Protein Binding"
  subtitle="Sam Houston State University · Lab Manager & Research Assistant · Aug 2023 – Aug 2025"
  tags={['VTE', 'RED', 'Protein Binding', 'HPLC Method Validation', 'ADME/DMPK']}
  year="2023 – 2025"
  description="Designed a vapor-phase binding assay for a volatile cyanide-antidote metabolite. Turned DMDS's instability from the thing that breaks the measurement into the thing that makes it work."
  prevStudy={{ title: 'Analytical Method Development in cGMP Manufacturing', href: '/case-studies/anant' }}
  nextStudy={{ title: 'Computational Protein Binding of DMTS and DMDS', href: '/case-studies/dmds-computational' }}
>

  <p>
    Dimethyl trisulfide (DMTS) is a garlic-derived compound being developed as an intramuscular cyanide antidote, a field-deployable alternative to the IV antidotes emergency medicine currently relies on. In the swine studies from Bebarta et al., roughly half of the administered DMTS is converted in blood to dimethyl disulfide (DMDS) by donating sulfur to cyanide, so understanding how DMDS behaves in plasma is essential for predicting the antidote's overall pharmacokinetics. My thesis, supervised by Dr. David E. Thompson and Dr. Ilona Petrikovics, characterized DMDS's binding to human serum albumin, the primary transport protein in blood and the one that governs whether a drug is free and active or sequestered and silent.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Rapid Equilibrium Dialysis (RED) plates had their own failure mode. The adhesive seals began debonding after about six hours at 37 &deg;C, exactly the incubation window the experiments required, which was catastrophic for a volatile analyte.
  </p>

  <div class="cs-image-wrap">
    <img
      src="/images/thesis/14_red_configuration.jpg"
      alt="RED configuration showing the Rapid Equilibrium Dialysis setup"
    />
    <p class="cs-caption">RAPID EQUILIBRIUM DIALYSIS CONFIGURATION</p>
  </div>

  <p>
    The experimental challenge is that DMDS is volatile. It boils at 110 &deg;C and doesn't want to stay in solution long enough for standard protein binding assays to work. Rather than force it into a method it doesn't fit, I helped refine a two-chamber assay that uses the volatility itself as the mechanism of equilibration: Vapor Transfer Equilibrium (VTE). One chamber holds the formulated drug, the other holds protein. They share a headspace but no liquid contact. DMDS equilibrates through the vapor phase while the non-volatile surfactant and protein stay put, turning the drug's instability from the thing that breaks the measurement into the thing that makes it work.
  </p>

  <div class="cs-image-wrap">
    <img
      src="/images/thesis/13_vte_setup.jpg"
      alt="Two-chamber Vapor Transfer Equilibrium apparatus showing drug chamber and protein chamber sharing a sealed headspace"
    />
    <p class="cs-caption">VAPOR TRANSFER EQUILIBRIUM APPARATUS</p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Running VTE alongside RED, I triangulated DMDS's behavior from two complementary angles. Both pointed to weak binding between DMDS and albumin. The more interesting finding came from the methodology itself. When VTE results looked flat, I suspected the assay before the biology and traced the lost signal to surface partitioning: DMDS was silently adsorbing onto the walls of the polypropylene container. Statistical analysis quantified losses at 25% over 270 minutes (p &lt; 0.001); an acetonitrile wash of the emptied containers recovered about 6% of the lost material, showing that most of it was going somewhere else, likely headspace volatilization or more complex surface effects.
  </p>

  <p>
    A parallel laser light scattering study found that the formulation itself was destabilizing, with systematic scattering decline over seven days suggesting micellar restructuring.
  </p>

  <div class="cs-image-wrap">
    <img
      src="/images/thesis/10_laser_setup.jpg"
      alt="Laser light scattering setup used to assess DMDS emulsion stability, showing green laser passing through solution in cuvette"
    />
    <p class="cs-caption">LASER SCATTERING SETUP<br />DMDS SOLUTION STABILITY MEASUREMENT</p>
  </div>

  <p>
    The work produced a validated High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC) method for DMDS quantification, a diagnostic framework for recognizing surface partitioning and emulsion artifacts in volatile-analyte assays, and VTE itself as a transferable method for any future volatile drug candidate. These methods now feed into the CounterACT-funded DMTS program at SHSU and its collaborating institutions.
  </p>

